observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to instruct the:

(a) accountable officers to settle immediately all their cash advances which are due for liquidation; 

(b) Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to continue on withholding the salaries of accountable officers who fail to timely liquidate their cash advances; 

(c) Municipal Accountant to:

strictly enforce rules in the granting utilization and liquidation cash advances per COA Circular 97-002;

 (ii) remind or issue demand letters to those who have not liquidated their cash advances on time; and

 (iii) spearhead the request for write off of unliquidated cash advances for those that are eligible for write off subject to COA rules and regulations on the writing off of accounts.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to instruct the: 

(a) Municipal Accountant to (i) report and disclose in the quarterly and year-end financial statements the status of donations-in-kind received; 

(ii) the offices concerned for the submission of report to the oversight bodies on any cash and in-kind donations officially received from the donors; 

(b) Property Officer to maintain adequate records for donations-in-kind and submit to the Municipal Accountant a status report thereof as at end of every quarter; and 

(c) Municipal Accountant, MDRRMO Head and the Property Officer to henceforth coordinate for the proper accounting of cash and in-kind donations in accordance with applicable rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate and ensure the: 

(a) strict observance of the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of all cash advances; 

(b) facilitation of request for write off the accounts that already meet the criteria for write off pursuant to COA rules and regulations; 



(c) withholding of salaries of accountable officers who will fail to comply with the directive or demand for liquidation; and 



(d) sending of demand letters regularly to the AOs with long outstanding cash advances.

We reiterate our previous recommendations that the Local Chief Executive ensure that: 

(a) effective cash programming is applied to facilitate the proper handling of cash such that it is available when needed for payment of obligations and at the same time, optimize its utilization; 



(b) austerity measures are adopted and restraint and prudence are observed in the disbursements of funds to improve the cash position of the Municipality; 

(c) trust funds are used solely for the purpose it was created or received; and 

(d) revenue collection measures are intensified to increase cash flow.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

(a) the accountable officers who are still in the service to settle immediately all their cash advances which are due for liquidation; 





(b) the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to (i) send demand letters and withhold the salaries of accountable officers who will fail to comply with the directive or demand for liquidation;

(ii) ensure the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of all cash advances in accordance with the existing rules and regulations; and 

(iii) request for write off the accounts that already meet the criteria for write off pursuant to COA rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the: 

(a) collectors concerned explanation why they should not be meted disciplinary sanctions for failing to remit their collections on time; 

(b) relieve the collectors concerned of their collecting functions; and 

(c) Municipal Treasurer to strengthen internal control on the handling, deposit and reporting of collections such that errors and irregularities may easily be detected by (a) segregating incompatible functions in the distribution of work load to cash/collection personnel; 

(b) seeing to it that the Date column of the RCD is filled out in the report preparation to timely monitor the reporting of collections and deposits; 

(c) requiring submission of monthly RAAF; and 

(d) enforcing strong internal control in the issuance of accountable forms, recording and depositing of collections and submission of reports to comply with the provisions set forth under Section 32 of the Manual on NGAs for LGUs.

We reiterated our recommendations that Municipal Local School Board should:
ensure continuously the proper charging  and allocation of disbursements to SEF;
prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;
request for inputs from the DepEd official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund; and
maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary.

We recommended that the;
Management procure its common-use supplies from the PS – DBM in compliance with AO No. 17 and Section 53(5) of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
Municipal Mayor require the BAC to prepare and submit to the GPPB the Procuring Monitoring Report in printed and electronic format within fourteen (14) calendar days after the end of each semester in compliance with Section 12.2 of the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act No. 9184.

We recommended and management agreed that Members of the Municipal Local School Board:

prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and refrain from accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;

request for inputs from the DepEd official/School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of laws, rules and regulations prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;

maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the PPAs, and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary; and

coordinate with the Property Offices of both the LGU and the DepEd to strengthen the controls on property accountability to monitor the clearances of those of the DepEd personnel who are retiring, resigning or terminating their employments.
